description.text:
If you have a WASP 3d printer, and you use the clay extruder, you must use a 19 wrench to unmount the front tube joint. Standard 19 wrench are big and heavy, so I created this one that is more agile and comfortable.

Print suggestions.
Use 0.4 or 0.35 mm nozzle, 0.2 layer height, min. 4 shells, 1,4 top and bottom thickness and 22% infill. If you place the wrench in his natural position on print bed (see 2nd image) no supports are needed. Add min. 10 brim perimeters in 1' layer if you print the wrench in ABS.

Detailed instructions here: http://www.cosmo3d.it/la-chiave-da-19-che-mancava-al-kit-wasp-per-l-argilla.html

description.text:
I challenged myself to design a 3D printer from scratch. My goal wasn't to reinvent the wheel, just to get something that works. This isn't the full design yet, but it's pretty close to finished and I'll update this post in the future. I'm printing structural parts on a Monoprice Select Mini, but everything else is from Amazon or local hardware stores.

I've also included a file for a jig to splice GT2 belts. It was mainly an exercise for me to switch from AutoCAD 2017 to Inventor 2017 for 3D modeling, but I'm sure someone could get use out of it.

List of parts I ordered from Amazon can be found here: http://a.co/iCZZ74D

Note: The cover image is only a render of what I've done so far. To do: Power/electronics enclosure, z-axis

UPDATE 3/7/17: I've uploaded revised parts for the XY gantry. After doing some test work reaming out the bearing holes with a drill press, I've edited the pilot holes to be much smaller to aid in center-finding. I've also put fillets on every edge that won't be up against the frame for a more polished look.

Press fitting is a great way to assemble parts without the need for adhesives or fasteners. Make sure the holes you drill for press-fitting rods and bearings are slightly more narrow than the part going in. The PETG I'm using for this project does a great job of flexing around the parts. Use a flat-faced vice for bearings, and a rubber mallet for guide rods. I also have a set of countersink bits I'll use to put a slight chamfer on the linear bearing holes to help them guide themselves in.

8mm rods: use a 5/16" drill bit
15mm OD linear bearings: 37/64" drill bit
22mm OD bearings: 55/64" forstner bit
5/8" OD Linear bearings (for the 3/8" vertical guide rods I'll use): 39/64"

description.text:
The following tutorial allows students to 3D print mathematical graphs using the free-online graphing calculator Desmos.

Desmos can be found at https://www.desmos.com/calculator

Desmos is a great learning tool because it is free to use and will work on any device that your students have access to. There is a even a iPAD app as well as a chrome extension for those students with Chrome Books.

Note: Desmos works well for graphing and printing 2-Dimensional graphs, but for 3-Dimensional mathematical representations read through Henry Segermans paper titled 3D printing for mathematical visualisation which can be found at: http://www.ms.unimelb.edu.au/~segerman/papers/3d_printed_visualisation.pdf
NGSS CCSS

3D printing mathematical computations can allow students to visualize, manipulate and better understand the concepts they are learning. Not only can Desmos be used to 3D students computations, but students can be given design challenges to utilize their graphs for various purposes. A simple example of this would be for students learning how to graph circles with specific areas. Students can 3D print their circles that need to fit a certain number of predetermined objects within like jelly beans or skittles. Desmos can be used for the following classes.
Pre-Algebra, Algebra 1 and 2, Trigonometry, Geometry, Pre-calculus, Calculus (AP), Statistics

Step 1) Create a design in Desmos:
For Desmos Tutorials visit http://learn.desmos.com/ Step 2) Set up the image for taking a Screen-Shot
  • Remove the background grid (unless you want the grid to be printed) by choosing the wrench in the upper right corner. Un-click the round grid, x-axis and y-axis. If you don’t remove these, they will get converted to part of the 3D design. (Image 1)
    -Choose "Projector Mode" which will make the graph lines thicker and easier for 3D printing.
    • Step 3) Take a screen shot of just your graph using the commands for the type of computer you are using. You can find how to to do this on your computer by visiting https://www.take-a-screenshot.org/ (Image 2) Image 1 Image 2

To be able to 3D print the mathematical graphs you will need to change the screen shot images first into an .SVG file (Scalable Vector Graphic)

Step 3) Go to http://picsvg.com/ . Here you will be able to upload your screen shot and convert it to an .SVG file all while being able to view the .SVG before downloading. This is a feature that other converting sites like http://image.online-convert.com/ don't have. (Image 3)

Step 4) Once you have downloaded the .SVG file you can now import it into your CAD program of choice. The image below had the model imported into TinkerCAD where a student could not manipulate the model even further if desired. (Image 4)

Step 5) Within the CAD program you choose students can add a back to their model, make it thicker, taller or whatever change is necessary for your lessons outcomes.

Step 6) Once the students 3D model is finished all that remains is to save the file for 3D printing. This will most often be an .STL or .OBJ file format. (Image 5)

I've made this little bicycle to be relatively strong, with movable parts.
I've printed all the parts with success. Supports only needed for rear frame.
You can see the video here: http://youtu.be/AnqlYZzgOo0
Update: assembling finished! Well, I only have natural color PLA, but I think it's nice anyway... :)
Added a new set of cranks and pedals - new fit. Not tested.
Now, you can print the rear wheel with the sprocket in one piece. I've added a modified version of the rear frame, too. If you want to modify it, the original Sketchup file was added.

1 - Fit the chain ring into the cranks and then snap the pedals.
2 - Mount the 2 parts of the frame with the cranks set in place. Use 2 screws for that (2mm screw - 5mm length).
3 - Mount the front wheel in fork with a screw (2mm - 15mm length)
4 - Fit the sprocket in rear wheel and insert them in the rear frame. You will need to open it a little (be careful to not brake it). After that, fix the wheel with a screw (2mm - 20mm length)
5 -Place the saddle in place (glue it if you want)
6 - Insert the fork in the front frame and fix the handle bar with glue.
7 - For the chain you can use a rubber band or a piece of thin rope. Don't use a too stretchy rubber, or it will stretch a bit, even if your wheel is loose.
You will need to cut the rubber and slide it thru the clearance between the rear wheel and the frame (hollow part). It will lay right on the sprocket. Pass the upper end thru the upper frame connection and somehow glue the ends together. I achieved an almost perfect junction gluing the ends with cyanoacrylate based glue. Just a touch will do it.
The two indentations on the holow part will allow the 'chain' to pass through the frame. I've made this to shrink the frame sideways.
Notes: I have printed the big parts with .2 layer, 15% infill, 2 shells. The small ones I printed with .15 layer.
You can see the different hole sizes. So, insert the screws in the bigger ones.
Some sanding may be required to free the parts, specially the rear wheel.

description.text:
This is my first (public) fan duct design. I did a lot of prototypes and experimented with placement of the cooling jets. This kind of airflow seems to be the best so far. My theory is that with this placement the both airflows create a circular region of high speed moving air at the tip of the nozzle. Experiments showed that very few air is blown in direction to the bed and even less onto the heat block.

At first I went with more or less traditional designs similar to ring fan ducts. But after I got it to work I switched to a design which lets one view what is going on at the nozzle.

Caution: That design is meant to sit very low over the build plate. To optimally adjust it select the best fitting ring. Then you can use the screws of the radial fan to fine adjust and horizontal align the jets to the conical part of the nozzle.

In the pictures you can see my main test object. It is the top of the Polymaker pearl tower from here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2064029 . It is printed with very cheap PETg filament at 240° C and a base speed of 80 mm/s. This seems to be a nice test for cooling experiments. PLA is not as hard to print overall in comparison.

Beware tough: I found that I had to reduce the power of the cooling fan for many prints even down to 40%. In spite of the very small canals, the resulting cooling seems to be very strong. If it is to strong it may prevent good bounding between layers. I saw this typically with rectilinear infill.

• Print the original cyHead27mmNoPipes_010.stl.

X Axis:

  • Additional LM8UU.
  • Belt tension is constant through out the Z height.
  • Belt tension does not affect Z rods.
  • Belt Tensioner.
  • Extruder mounts higher, allowing for a bigger build area.
  • Z Axis endstop adjustable trigger.

Y Axis:

  • Smooth rods equally spaced.
  • Belt Tensioner.
  • Overall lower height allowing for bigger build area.
  • LM8UU Align perfectly.
  • Additional LM8UU.
  • Considerably lower noise levels.
  • LM8UU go on without zip ties.

Z Axis:

  • Stepper motors horizontally aligned.
  • Smooth Rod and M5 Threaded rod equaly spaced with X axis.

description.text:
After struggling to top up the screen wash in my car without it going all over the place, I decided that it called for a bespoke funnel to make the task easier. It is designed around a 2014 Audi A7 which has the screen wash bottle right next to one of the bonnet hinges making it awkward to pour from a 5 litre container.
The spout fits neatly into the filler neck of the bottle whilst the incorporated stand helps to steady the funnel leaving both hands free for pouring.
First world problems and all that, but hey, I've got a 3D printer so why not.

title: Anet A8_remixed_Z Endstop Fine Adjustment Leg

description.text:
I remixed Meermeneer's Z Endstop Fine Adjustment Leg (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1776429). I left the other two parts of the thing unmodified.

I replaced the two slots with holes to make it more robust. Since the stock screws have an angled bearing surface, tightening them down can wedge a slot apart or even split the whole bracket. The vertical M3 screw provides all of the adjustability needed, thus it negates the need for slots (given that there is a similar hole pattern on the motor). The holes on this remix are spaced 31.5mm on center, which is what I measured on my screws.

For the slots to work [in this application], the screws (and countersinks) need their bearing surfaces to be perpendicular to the turning plane, OR, the piece would need to be made wider in order to have a sufficient amount of material to resist the flexing imposed by the screwhead.

Also, since this bracket becomes part of the motor mount, I wanted something a little more solid without having to add extra material. In fact, it might be slightly shorter, so a longer screw may be needed depending on how your bed is set up. I would recommend a screw to accommodate a lock-nut above and below the bracket, because then you'll NEVER have to think about it again. (An extra 10 cents can buy a lot of peace of mind).

title: Hanging Rod / Spool Holder for Steel Shelving (Muscle Rack / Edsal)

description.text:
These are holders for a hanging rod to attach to a steel shelving unit. Specifically I'm using on a Muscle Rack UR4824HPSVL5 which seems to be a rebrand of an identical unit from Edsal. It uses 3/4in doweling as a rod, since it's cheap and readily avalible at most hardware stores. I've included the FreeCAD file though so you can adjust it to fit whatever you need. It's a little oddly shaped so that I can actually fit in on my printer, the MP Mini. Because of the triangle shape i can just barely print two at a time on it. The picture shows using it to hold spools but i've got a pair holding a roll of butcher paper, another pair holding paper towels, and of course a number with spools. Because they fit both ways they're pretty handy.

The rails on these racks are not as consistent as i thought, but this size seems to work on most. Sometimes it's rather loose and other times quite a tight fit. You can actually mount these either way on the rail and they'll be pretty solid. I'm using about 50% infill ABS just to be sure though. The upper section is thin for two reasons - on a tight rail you can use them as arms to actually get the thing to clip on or release, and being thin allows the least amount of interference if you need to use shelving at the same time (which I havent actually tried yet on this revision.). The holes save filament and are sized to also fit a 3/4in dowel, so you can put smaller things closer to the rail to keep some stress off of it.
3/4in dowel or other rod of appropriate length.

So, this file is basically one sketch in FreeCad, so it might be a little confusing to edit. The important constraints are the 101mm one from the center of the snap fit dowel holder to the edge of the triangular hole for the shelf part of the rail. This keeps the part able to fit a 100mm dia. spool. The 115mm overall width constraint keeps the part able to print on the MP Mini, without it you can adjust this thing to be quite a bit smaller. The 51.5mm constraint is the one you will probably have to change to make this work with other shelving, as long as it uses a similar profile. The dowel holes are all mirrored, and are a little big at 9.8mm since they can run a little big sometimes. The snap fit one at the end is smaller so it stays snug.

Expandable eSun spool drawer system. Like several other upcycling spool drawer projects, this one is for eSun spools.

While this is not a direct remix of any of the listed project, I wanted to include them as the inspiration for several of the design aspects of this project. There is one piece, Bearing_wheel.stl, that is a direct copy of the Universal Stand-Alone Filament Spool Holder. It was the inspiration for the turn-table it uses and I didn't want to reinvent the wheel so to speak.

There are two drawer designs. One with a place to place a label and another without the label holder. If you are only using one spool, the you do not need the extension or link file.

The drill guide fits over the ribs on the inner part of the spool. It is a tight fit and may need to be worked a bit to get it on. Start with a small bit and drill a pilot hole. I used a 2mm bit followed by a 3.5mm.

The drawer pegs should fit tightly in the holes on the drawers. The bottom of the peg is slightly larger than the top. To help identify top and bottom, there is a hole on the bottom of the peg.

The wheels are kept in place with a bit of 1.75mm filament. It is a push-fit and should hold without any glue. However, if you find them working out, a small drop of super glue on the outside will fix them in place. Just make sure none get on the inside and glues the wheel in place.

The spindle peg has a slot in it to allow adjustment after the spindle is attached. You can tighten it down so there is not as much free play between the spindle and base.

If you want to have more than one spool, print an extension for each spool you wish to add. The link pins are optional are are used to keep the spools locked together when they turn.

title: Modular Castle Kit - Lego compatible V2
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a new version of the Modular Castle Kit - Lego Compatible, a kit to assemble Lego compatible modules into castles and strongholds. You can print just one, several or all components and then play at castle construction, mixing in your own Lego. You can hook together modules like in the picture used to advertise this thing (use simple Lego bricks as connectors) or you can create much wilder "mix with any Lego" structures or you could create a village with different buildings. Some modules are designed to be stacked on top of each other.

Improvements:

  • Heights are more standardized
  • Lego Persona fit inside the rooms
  • New components

There are three types of components:
(1) with easy to print base plate,
(2) with Lego-compatible base plate (stackable)
(3, new) "lighter" stackable versions (better vertical fit, faster print)

I printed most, but not all of the modules. However, I then also made some minor changes to most of the printed ones and there still may be a few minor glitches. Please examine a thing before you print it.

When I have time (not likely in the very near future) I will provide some online documentation.

Printer:

Felix Pro 1

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.25

Infill:

20 to 25%

Notes:

Make sure that the first layer sticks well, in particular when printing Lego-compatible bases (nibbles underneath). A few things to to:

  • Make your first layer 125-150% or something that is equivalent. Most platforms are uneven (0.05mm waves do have an impact) and you will have to compensate for that.
  • Add glue to the platform (e.g. Pritt extra strong) or hairspray
  • Add 10 degs or more to standard printing temperature, e.g. PLA at 205
  • Move the print head closer to the platform, e.g. for my self-calibrating printer I add this to the end of the start code: G1 Z-.05 F3000 or sometimes G1 Z-.1 F3000. On a non calibrating printer, place two sheets of paper on the bed and make sure that the print head can move the upper sheet in every position, but without scratching.
  • You could use a raft for the modules that have 2x2 Lego feet, but removing these is a pain...

Speed:

  • Go very slowly for the first layer (about 15% of your normal speed).
  • Go slowly for the second layer (if your slicer allows)
  • Medium speed for the rest, e.g. 50mm/s or faster

Shells and layers:

  • 3 shells
  • 4 top layers (3 also can do)
  • 3 or 4 bottom layers.

Rafts and support

  • In principle, you do not need any form of support structure. Getting non-solvable plastic sticks out of Lego bases is too much of a pain... All important angles are steep enough and don't require wasting plastic inside of the towers.
  • However, we recommend printing the wizard tower on Lego feet with a raft (see one of the attached pictures). Also, make sure that Z dimension of your printer can handle these small and long towers.

Tune your settings with the included standard 4x2 calibration brick.

One tower takes about 6 hours to print with these settings. I do not recommend printing with lower resolution because wait will be longer. If you print modules with a base plate, you can easily print 4 towers at the same time, in about a day.

Final advice

  • Avoid printing with warping plastic (e.g. ABS) or PLA that has lots of paint inside (it may warp and not stick)
  • If you print pieces with Lego feet or bases, you really must make sure that the first layer sticks well. Best strategies are (a) calibrating the platform (b) 150 layer thickness (c) less than 10mm/s. After the third layer you can go much faster.
  • Beginners could start printing towers that have flat bottoms.

Fit with real Lego (TM)

Fit is about right for printing with 0.25 resolution and medium-fast quality printing. The blocks are maybe a bit too tight for fit with Lego. In that case, heat the piece with a heat gun (or maybe a strong hair dryer), then gently press onto Lego (TM). If the fit is too loose, change the slicer settings (or much better, generate your own version with OpenSCAD).

Print the 4x2 Lego calibration brick first.

Design notes

I am not much of a 3D modeler and do not spend much time on it. My design goal was to create something that helps kid's imagination and constructive mind and that is (fairly) easy to print. The first version was created in 2012 using our Doblo Factory code ().
(http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2106)

I used this library to create several other things, e.g. the thesis project management kit published here (thing:33001)

In 2012/13, Daniel M. Taub refactored the Doblo code (great work) and added some extra functionality. In 2013/2015 I made some minor modifications to it, but I never got the hang of github :(

I finally decided redoing this Lego kit since I noticed that it is still popular :)

OpenSCAD code / tuning / creating

I only included the scad file that generates these blocks. It gives you an idea on how these modules are built. A typical tower includes mostly about 20-30 function calls, generating Lego block elements plus some openScad "hand code".

If you download the full Doblo Factory code (http://edutechwiki.unige.ch/en/Doblo_factory, also see the URL in the scad) file, you can:

  • tune dimensions, e.g. various Lego-compatible nibble and wall thickness parameters (lib/doblo-params.scad)
  • produce DUPLO structures instead (SCALE=1;) (example_castle_kit/castle_generation.scad)
  • create your own castle modules (ext/castle-kit-2-0.scad)
